A university press asked me to review a book manuscript, and the author &ldquo;has asked that we not use electronic copies.&rdquo; So they&rsquo;re going to send me a hard copy.
My response: &ldquo;If you only give me a paper copy, I&rsquo;m going to just scan it and toss the paper. That seems like a waste of time (and paper and postage).&rdquo;
I should probably have said, &ldquo;Then forget it.&rdquo;
Their response included, &ldquo;What you do with it when it arrives I am just going to take a hear-no-evil approach to.

This afternoon I refused a request from the American Journal of Human Genetics to review a paper, though the abstract was extremely interesting. AJHG is published by Elsevier, and I&rsquo;d signed the declaration at http://thecostofknowledge.com to not publish or review for Elsevier journals. If only AJHG were still with the University of Chicago Press&hellip;
